  "prompt": "What would cause a comminuted fracture in the elbow?",
  "response": "A comminuted fracture in the elbow can be caused by several factors:\n\n1. High-impact trauma\n- Severe car accidents\n- Falls from significant heights\n- Direct, forceful blows to the elbow\n- Sports-related injuries with high-energy impact\n\n2. Specific types of accidents\n- Motorcycle crashes\n- Industrial or construction accidents\n- Workplace accidents involving heavy machinery\n\n3. Sports injuries\n- Contact sports (football, rugby)\n- Extreme sports with potential for high-impact falls\n- Collision sports with direct contact\n\n4. Underlying conditions\n- Osteoporosis (weakens bones, making them more susceptible to fracture)\n- Bone cancer\n- Bone disorders that reduce bone density\n\n5. Specific mechanisms of injury\n- Direct compression\n- Twisting or rotational forces\n- Sudden, extreme bending of the elbow\n- Crushing injuries\n\n6. Age-related factors\n- Elderly individuals with reduced bone density\n- Children with developing bone structures\n\nThe severity and specific cause will determine treatment, which often involves surgical intervention, immobilization, and rehabilitation.",
